<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n11143f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n11" href="#n11143f">N11 (VI.B.5)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n11all.htm#n11143f"> 143(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> auroch?</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Parlant de ces menhirs, Geoffroy de Monmouth, le chroniqueur des plus vieilles traditions celtiques, dit: &ldquo;Ces pierres sont magiques. Des g&eacute;ants les apport&egrave;rent autrefois.&rdquo; Mais quels g&eacute;ants? Peut-&ecirc;tre ces Hyperbor&eacute;ens venus des r&eacute;gions bor&eacute;ales dont parlent les traditions grecques, premiers dompteurs du cheval et du chien, inventeurs des haches de silex, de la fronde et de l&apos;arc, grands chasseurs <mark>d&apos;aurochs</mark>, qui allaient devant eux, ivres de lumi&egrave;re et d&apos;espace.&rdquo; <br><font color="green">[Speaking of these menhirs, Geoffroy de Monmouth, the chronicler of the oldest Celtic traditions, says: &ldquo;regions of which speak the Greek traditions, first tamer of the horse and the dog, inventors of the axes of flint, the sling and the bow, big hunters of aurochs, who went before them, drunk of light and space.&rdquo;]</font> <small> &Eacute;douard Schur&eacute;, <a name="ESLG" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ESLG"><cite title="source">Les Grandes L&eacute;gendes de France</cite></a> (1921, 1892) 205</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Aurochs. An extinct species of wild ox. The name was also incorrectly applied to the bison. </mm> </dd></dl>
